  <a href="#1" id="1">
   President Bush, filling a key overseas post, has decided to nominate a former CIA officer as ambassador to China, sources said Wednesday, 02/01/1989.
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   The choice is James R. Lilley, a career intelligence officer who served as CIA station chief in China when Bush headed the U.S. liaison office there in 1974-75.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   Lilley, 60, was born in China, the son of an American oilman working there.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   He has also served on the National Security Council staff, as head of the unofficial U.S. office in Taiwan and as a deputy assistant secretary of state for East Asia.
  </a>
